  "doc_id": "61553",
  "text": "A thylakoid, a membrane-bound compartment inside chloroplasts, is a place for primary reactions of photosynthesis. The thylakoid membrane contains the four major multisubunit protein complexes, PSI, PSII, ATP synthase complex and cytochrome b6/f complex. Around 100 proteins are controlling the reactions in thylakoid membranes. The proteins are mainly involved in the conversion of light energy to chemical energy, but several other proteins have a function in assembly, maintenance, and regulation of the four multiprotein complexes [CITATION_1] . Isolation and analysis of proteins located in thylakoid membrane can give an overview of the complex function of the membrane especially under stress conditions. Thylakoid membrane proteins were isolated from wild-type and mutant strains of Chlamydomonas reinhardtii and analyzed using proteomic techniques. More than 30 different spots were identified as light-harvesting complex proteins. The function of this protein in response to abiotic stress was reported in plants by Kono et al. [109] and Muneer et al. [CITATION_2] .",
